# 🔢 French Vocabulary — Numbers (Les Nombres)

Numbers in French are essential for dates, prices, time, and general conversation.  
Below is a breakdown by range with pronunciation tips and patterns.

---

## 🟢 0–20 (Les bases)

| Number | French | Pronunciation (approx.) |
|----------|----------|----------------|
| 0 | zéro | [zeh-ro] |
| 1 | un | [uh̃] |
| 2 | deux | [duh] |
| 3 | trois | [trwah] |
| 4 | quatre | [katr] |
| 5 | cinq | [sank] |
| 6 | six | [sees] |
| 7 | sept | [set] |
| 8 | huit | [weet] |
| 9 | neuf | [nuhf] |
| 10 | dix | [dees] |
| 11 | onze | [onz] |
| 12 | douze | [dooz] |
| 13 | treize | [trehz] |
| 14 | quatorze | [ka-torz] |
| 15 | quinze | [kanz] |
| 16 | seize | [sez] |
| 17 | dix-sept | [dees-set] |
| 18 | dix-huit | [dees-weet] |
| 19 | dix-neuf | [dees-nuhf] |
| 20 | vingt | [vuh̃] |

---

## 🟡 21–69 (Tens and pattern building)

| Tens | French | Example |
|-------|---------|---------|
| 20 | vingt | 21 → vingt et un |
| 30 | trente | 32 → trente-deux |
| 40 | quarante | 47 → quarante-sept |
| 50 | cinquante | 59 → cinquante-neuf |
| 60 | soixante | 66 → soixante-six |

🧠 **Note:** only “21, 31, 41, 51, 61” use *et un* (e.g., *trente et un*).

---

## 🔵 70–99 (Special pattern)

French uses **base-60 logic** for these:
- 70 = *soixante-dix* (60 + 10)
- 71 = *soixante et onze* (60 + 11)
- 80 = *quatre-vingts* (4 × 20)
- 90 = *quatre-vingt-dix* (80 + 10)

| Number | French | Meaning |
|----------|----------|----------|
| 70 | soixante-dix | 60 + 10 |
| 71 | soixante et onze | 60 + 11 |
| 80 | quatre-vingts | 4 × 20 |
| 81 | quatre-vingt-un | 80 + 1 |
| 90 | quatre-vingt-dix | 80 + 10 |
| 99 | quatre-vingt-dix-neuf | 80 + 19 |

---

## 🟣 100 and beyond

| Number | French | Notes |
|----------|----------|----------|
| 100 | cent | no *s* unless plural (*deux cents*) |
| 200 | deux cents | add *s* only if no number follows |
| 1000 | mille | never takes *s* |
| 1 000 000 | un million | plural → *des millions* |
| 1 000 000 000 | un milliard | billion (in French sense) |

---

## 💡 Tips
- Don’t pronounce final *t* or *s* in most numbers (e.g. *deux*, *trois*).  
- Hyphens connect all parts from 17 upward (*vingt-trois, trente-cinq*).  
- French numbers use a **space** instead of a comma for thousands → *1 500*, not *1,500*.  

---

## 🧭 Quick Examples
- *J’ai vingt-cinq ans.* → I am 25 years old.  
- *Il est né en mille neuf cent quatre-vingt-dix.* → He was born in 1990.  
- *Le billet coûte quatre-vingt-sept euros.* → The ticket costs 87 euros.  
- *Nous sommes trois dans la famille.* → There are three of us in the family.

---
